<HEADLINE>
<P>
JOHN L. MCCREA; NAVAL AIDE TO PRESIDENT ROOSEVELT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
John L. McCrea, 98, a retired vice admiral who was the naval aide to President 
Franklin D. Roosevelt during the first year of World War II. McCrea, who later 
became an aide to Roosevelt at the Casablanca Conference during World War II, 
left the White House in 1943 to become the first captain of the battleship 
Iowa, the ship that also carried Roosevelt to conferences in Cairo and Tehran. 
</P>
<P>
On Nov. 21, 1918, as watch officer aboard the battleship New York, McCrea 
entered in the ship's log the surrender of the Imperial German Navy's High Seas 
Fleet at the end of World War I. McCrea graduated from the U.S. Naval Academy 
in 1915, and left the service in 1953 as commandant of the 1st Naval District. 
After leaving the service, he joined John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance Co. as 
vice president for client relations, retiring in 1966. In Needham, Mass., on 
Jan. 25. 
</P>
</TEXT>
