<HEADLINE>
<P>
VIRGINIA FIRM TO STUDY SHUTTLE TANK PROJECT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The National Aeronautics and Space Administration has granted a small Virginia 
company the right to do research and development for using spent space shuttle 
fuel tanks as a platform for military, civilian and commercial experiments. 
</P>
<P>
The agreement, signed with Global Outpost of Alexandria, is the first for using 
the 154-foot-long tanks, which now are destroyed in their plunge through the 
atmosphere. The tanks carry the 528,000 gallons of liquid hydrogen and liquid 
oxygen that carry the shuttle into orbit. 
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, NASA will be reimbursed for any work it does for Global 
Outpost, a firm formed in 1988 in response to President Reagan's commercial 
space initiative. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
