<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRETT STUNS ALL WITH SHARP DEMAND FOR MORE MONEY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By STEVE CAMERON, KANSAS CITY STAR AND TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Kansas City Royals superstar George Brett has stunned his employers, teammates 
and fans with a sharply worded demand for a heftier contract. 
</P>
<P>
Brett's remarks, which became public after an interview with the Spokane 
(Wash.) 
</P>
<P>
Spokesman-Review, included a suggestion that he should be traded if the Royals 
will not renegotiate his current deal of $1.5 million a year. 
</P>
<P>
Brett also listed six teams -- Los Angeles, Boston, St. Louis, San Diego, Texas 
and the Chicago Cubs -- he would be willing to play for if the Royals want to 
trade him rather than pay him. 
</P>
<P>
Brett signed a so-called lifetime deal in 1984, an arrangement that includes a 
$1.5-million salary through 1991 with options for two years beyond that. 
Real-estate deals and other considerations were included that would keep Brett 
on the Royals' payroll indefinitely. 
</P>
<P>
But Brett, 36, apparently has been chafing over huge salaries being paid to 
players without records approaching his own. So last Friday, on a business trip 
to Spokane, Brett made his demands known to the Spokesman-Review, which ran the 
story Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
"I understand that, yeah, I did sign a contract," Brett was quoted as saying. 
"I've got to play out that contract, and I will honor that contract, but right 
now I'm not looking forward to going to spring training unless my attitude 
changes." 
</P>
<P>
Brett characterized his relationship with the Royals as shaky and said the 
contract problems are disturbing his off-season conditioning routine. 
</P>
<P>
Royals General Manager John Schuerholz confirmed that he had spoken with both 
Brett and his agent-brother Bobby in a frantic 24-hour period that began 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
"I talked to George very briefly," Schuerholz said. "At the moment, that's all 
I will say on the subject. I intend to talk to him again." 
</P>
